segment.source: Let's use the competency questions from the previous lesson as a terminology source for beginning to specify terms in our ontology.
Open the PDF documents under "Card-Sorting Activity."
Start with the first file ("Bibliographic Record Unlabeled").
You will see a series of numbered cards with information extracted from a MARC 21 Bibliographic record for the novel Cien años de soledad.
The cards are in the order they appear in the record.
When a card has decimal numbers, it means that the data elements come from the same field.
Using the numbers, group the cards into categories.
Try to identify the types of entities that are represented.
Once you identify a group, give it a name and write down the criteria used for creating it.
For example, "New York" is a type of Place (or City, or Populated Place, which are specific kinds of Place).

segment.source: The domain of a property defines the class it starts from, whereas the range defines the class it points to.
Simple network diagram showing two nodes (Domain on the left and Range on the right) linked by an edge labeled Property.
The domain and range of a property can also be defined.
A property domain limits the individuals that property can apply to.
The range of a property limits the individuals it can take as its object.

segment.source: Data in spreadsheets is easy to work with and share, but it lacks defined semantics.
Example inspired by the book Linked Data:

ID, Name, User, Inst, and Loc.

segment.source: Individuals are instances or members of a class.
For example, an individual named Deborah can be described as a member of the class Person, and the property hasEmployer can be used to relate her to the individual StanfordUniversity.

segment.source: An ontology allows us to define a data model that reflects reality in all its complexity.
For its part, a controlled vocabulary has a simpler intent.
It defines a list of concepts that can have hierarchical relationships, but that do not reflect a view of the world in an explicit way.
However, controlled vocabularies can also be created using linked data standards.
The Simple Knowledge Organization System (SKOS) was created to design thesauri and controlled vocabularies in RDF.

mda:metaGroup.mda:meta: EBSCO Linked Data Training, Day 1, Lesson 4 (PT)

segment.source: Properties can be used to establish relationships between individuals or individuals and literal data values.
Properties are usually written with a lowercase letter, or using "Camel Case" (e.g., accountName).

A more complex illustration showing small network graph of give connected nodes.
All nodes are circles with the same pastel-orange color.
On the left, there are two nodes, labeled book1 and book2.
In the middle are three nodes that are the object of triples for which book1 and book2 are the subjects.
Book1 has two edges, labeled language and creator.
The language edge points to a node labeled lang1, which has an edge pointing to the literal value Español.
The creator edge points to a node labeled person1, which, in turn, has an edge labeled first-name pointing to the value Gabriel and an edge labeled family-name pointing to the value García Márquez.
Person1 also has an edge, labeled language, point to the node labeled lang1.
Finally, book2 has two edges, creator and subject.
The creator edge points to person1 and the subject edge points to another node, which is labeled concept1.

BIBFRAME's relationship to other metadata standards
Network diagram showing the relationship between BIBFRAME and other metadata standards.
The diagram depicts a graph that starts with a square node labeled BIBFRAME on the left, with edges depicting relationships to OWL, RDA, MARC 21, RDF, AACR2, and IFLA LRM.
BIBFRAME uses RDF, uses in part OWL, codifies RDA, replaces and translates MARC 21, and is inspired by IFLA LRM.
OWL formalizes RDF; RDA uses in part RDF, replaces AACR2, and implements IFLA LRM.
The 1.0 version of BIBFRAME was based on two main classes:
Items in BIBFRAME 1.0 were represented as Annotations.
Network diagram showing a high-level overview of the BIBFRAME 1.0 model, divided between Work and Instance.
The 2.0 version of BIBFRAME added new classes for Item and Event, among others.
Network diagram showing a high-level overview of the BIBFRAME 2.0 model, divided among Work, Instance, and Item.
BIBFRAME can accommodate the IFLA Library Reference Model (LRM), and by extension RDA, by allowing us to make distinctions among Work, Expression, Manifestation (Instance in BIBFRAME) and Item.

The diagram shows the relationships among Work, Expression, Manifestation (Instance in BIBFRAME) and Item.

A single MARC bibliographic record includes fields that map to different levels of the BIBFRAME semantic model (ontology).
Diagram showing the BIBFRAME 2.0 model on the left and slivers of MARC 21 bibliographic fields on the right (fields 130, 245, 260, and 300).
Arrows extend from the fields to the BIBFRAME 2.0 entities to which they correspond:
130 maps to Work; 245 maps to Work and Instance; 260 maps to Instance; 300 maps to Instance and Item.
